<subsection xml:id="subsec-angles-at-a-point">
    <title>Angles Around a Point</title>
    <p>
        Angles at a point are formed when two or more angles meet at the same point (vertex), creating a full turn. 
        The most important property of angles at a point is that their sum always adds up to <m>360^\circ</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
        Here are the different types of angles that can be formed at a point:
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term>Full Rotation (360Â° Angle) </term> - A complete turn around a point, forming a circle.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term>Vertically Opposite Angles</term> - When two lines cross at a point, they create pairs of equal angles that are opposite each other.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term>Adjacent Angles</term> - Two angles that share a common side and a common vertex. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term>Complementary Angles</term> - Two angles that add up to <m>90^\circ</m>, forming a right-angle when placed together.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term>Supplementary Angles</term> - Two angles that add up to <m>180^\circ</m>, forming a straight line when combined.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <term>Work in pairs.</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Trace and cut out the fugure below.     
                        </p>
                        <image width="50%">
                            <shortdescription>Angles at a point</shortdescription>
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \draw(-3,-2) coordinate (a)--(3,2)coordinate(b);
                                        \draw(3,-2)coordinate(c)--(-3,2)coordinate(d);
                                        \node at(0,0.5) {a};
                                        \node at(0.5,0){b};
                                        \node at (0,-0.5){c};
                                        \node at (-0.5,0){d};
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Use a protractor to measure the following angles:
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\angle a</m> 
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\angle b</m> 
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\angle c</m> 
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\angle d</m> 
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Identify the pair of angles that are:
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Vertically opposite
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Adjacent
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the sum of <m>\angle a</m> , <m>\angle b</m> , <m>\angle c</m> and <m>\angle d.</m> 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Share your work with other learners in class.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
                
            <p>
                <term>Key Takeaway</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\angle a</m>  is vertically opposite to <m>\angle c</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\angle b</m>  is vertically opposite to <m>\angle d</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Vertically opposite angles are equal.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\angle a</m> = <m>\angle c</m> 
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\angle b</m> = <m>\angle d</m> 
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\angle a</m>  is adjacent to <m>\angle b</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\angle b</m>  is adjacent to <m>\angle c</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\angle c</m>  is adjacent to <m>\angle d</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\angle d</m>  is adjacent to <m>\angle a</m>
            </p>
        </statement>            
    </activity>
                        
    <example>
        <statement>
        <p>
            Work out the value of the angle marked <m>x</m>  in the figure 
        </p>

        <image>
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \draw(105:-2cm) -- (105:3cm);
                    \draw(-3,-2) -- (3,2);
                    \draw(160:0) -- (160:3cm);
                    \draw(0,0) -- (34:.55) arc (34:105:.55);
                    \draw(68:0.9cm) node {$x$};
                    \draw(0,0) --(105:.45) arc (105:160:.45);
                    \draw(120:0.9cm) node {$45^\circ$};
                    \draw(0,0) -- (160:.5) arc (160:214:.5);
                    \draw(195:0.9cm) node{$70^\circ$};
                    \draw(0,0) -- (214:.65) arc (214:285:.65);
                    \draw(250:.9cm) node {$60^\circ$};
                    \draw(0,0) -- (285:.45) arc (285:394:.45);
                    \draw(350:.9cm) node {$125^\circ$};   
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                Angles <m>x,45^\circ, 70^\circ, 60^\circ \text{and } 125^\circ</m> meet at a point. 

            </p>

            <p>
                Therefore:
            </p>

            <p>
                <me>
                x +45^\circ + 70^\circ + 60^\circ + 125^\circ = 360^\circ
                </me>
                
            </p>

            <p>
                <me>
                    x + 300^\circ = 360^\circ  
                </me>   
            </p>

            <p>
                <me>
                    x + 300^\circ - 300^\circ = 360^\circ - 300^\circ  
                </me>
            </p>

            <p>
                <me>
                    x = 60^\circ
                </me>
                
            </p>

        </solution>
    </example>

